# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol] It is a solvent for dyes, nitrocellulose, paints, inks, and resins.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol] It is a component of wood stains for wood, for setting the twist and conditioning yarns and cloth, in textile printing, textile soaps, lacquers, penetration enhancer in cosmetics, drying varnishes and enamels, and brake fluids.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol] It is used to determine the saponification values of oils and as a neutral solvent for mineral oil-soap and mineral oil-sulfated oil mixtures (giving fine dispersions in water).
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol] It is also widely used as a solvent in a number of cosmetics and personal care products, including face cream, deodorant, makeup, hair dye, and sunless tanner.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/2-ethoxyethanol] 2-Ethoxyethanol is manufactured by the reaction of ethylene oxide with ethanol.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/2-ethoxyethanol] As with other glycol ethers, 2-ethoxyethanol has the useful property of being able to dissolve chemically diverse compounds.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/2-ethoxyethanol] It will dissolve oils, resins, grease, waxes, nitrocellulose, and lacquers.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/2-ethoxyethanol] This is an ideal property as a multi-purpose cleaner, and, therefore, 2-ethoxyethanol is used in products such as varnish removers and degreasing solutions.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] This temperature is required to supply the activation energy needed for combustion.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] The temperature at which a chemical ignites decreases as the pressure is decreased.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] Substances which spontaneously ignite in a normal atmosphere at naturally ambient temperatures are termed pyrophoric.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] Autoignition temperatures of liquid chemicals are typically measured using a 500-millilitre (18 imp fl oz; 17 US fl oz) flask placed in a temperature-controlled oven in accordance with the procedure described in ASTM E659.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] When measured for plastics, autoignition temperature can also be measured under elevated pressure and at 100% oxygen concentration.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] The resulting value is used as a predictor of viability for high-oxygen service.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] The main testing standard for this is ASTM G72.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] where *k* = thermal conductivity, *ρ* = density, and *c* = specific heat capacity of the material of interest, $T_{0}$ is the initial temperature of the material (or the temperature of the bulk material).
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] Temperatures vary widely in the literature and should only be used as estimates.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] Factors that may cause variation include partial pressure of oxygen, altitude, humidity, and amount of time required for ignition.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] Generally the autoignition temperature for hydrocarbon/air mixtures decreases with increasing molecular mass and increasing chain length.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] The autoignition temperature is also higher for branched-chain hydrocarbons than for straight-chain hydrocarbons.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The **boiling point** of a substance is the temperature at which the vapor pressure of a liquid equals the pressure surrounding the liquid and the liquid changes into a vapor.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point of a liquid varies depending upon the surrounding environmental pressure.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] A liquid in a partial vacuum, i.e., under a lower pressure, has a lower boiling point than when that liquid is at atmospheric pressure.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Because of this, water boils at 100 °C, rounded from scientific precision of 99.97 °C (211.95 °F), under standard pressure at sea level, but at 93.4 °C (200.1 °F) at 1,905 metres (6,250 ft) altitude.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] For a given pressure, different liquids will boil at different temperatures.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The **normal boiling point** (also called the **atmospheric boiling point** or the **atmospheric pressure boiling point**) of a liquid is the special case in which the vapor pressure of the liquid equals the defined atmospheric pressure at sea level, one atmosphere.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] At that temperature, the vapor pressure of the liquid becomes sufficient to overcome atmospheric pressure and allow bubbles of vapor to form inside the bulk of the liquid.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The **standard boiling point** has been defined by IUPAC since 1982 as the temperature at which boiling occurs under a pressure of one bar.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The heat of vaporization is the energy required to transform a given quantity (a mol, kg, pound, etc.) of a substance from a liquid into a gas at a given pressure (often atmospheric pressure).
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Liquids may change to a vapor at temperatures below their boiling points through the process of evaporation.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Evaporation is a surface phenomenon in which molecules located near the liquid's edge, not contained by enough liquid pressure on that side, escape into the surroundings as vapor.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] On the other hand, boiling is a process in which molecules anywhere in the liquid escape, resulting in the formation of vapor bubbles within the liquid.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] A *saturated liquid* contains as much thermal energy as it can without boiling (or conversely a *saturated vapor* contains as little thermal energy as it can without condensing).
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] If the pressure in a system remains constant (isobaric), a vapor at saturation temperature will begin to condense into its liquid phase as thermal energy (heat) is removed.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Similarly, a liquid at saturation temperature and pressure will boil into its vapor phase as additional thermal energy is applied.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point corresponds to the temperature at which the vapor pressure of the liquid equals the surrounding environmental pressure.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Thus, the boiling point is dependent on the pressure.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Boiling points may be published with respect to the NIST, USA standard pressure of 101.325 kPa (1 atm), or the IUPAC standard pressure of 100.000 kPa (1 bar).
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] At higher elevations, where the atmospheric pressure is much lower, the boiling point is also lower.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point increases with increased pressure up to the critical point, where the gas and liquid properties become identical.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point cannot be increased beyond the critical point.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Likewise, the boiling point decreases with decreasing pressure until the triple point is reached.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point cannot be reduced below the triple point.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] If the temperature in a system remains constant (an *isothermal* system), vapor at saturation pressure and temperature will begin to condense into its liquid phase as the system pressure is increased.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Similarly, a liquid at saturation pressure and temperature will tend to flash into its vapor phase as system pressure is decreased.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] There are two conventions regarding the *standard boiling point of water*: The *normal boiling point* is commonly given as 100 °C (212 °F) (actually 99.97 °C (211.9 °F) following the thermodynamic definition of the Celsius scale based on the kelvin) at a pressure of 1 atm (101.325 kPa).
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The IUPAC-recommended *standard boiling point of water* at a standard pressure of 100 kPa (1 bar) is 99.61 °C (211.3 °F).
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] For comparison, on top of Mount Everest, at 8,848 m (29,029 ft) elevation, the pressure is about 34 kPa (255 Torr) and the boiling point of water is 71 °C (160 °F).
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The Celsius temperature scale was defined until 1954 by two points: 0 °C being defined by the water freezing point and 100 °C being defined by the water boiling point at standard atmospheric pressure.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The higher the vapor pressure of a liquid at a given temperature, the lower the normal boiling point (i.e., the boiling point at atmospheric pressure) of the liquid.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The vapor pressure chart to the right has graphs of the vapor pressures versus temperatures for a variety of liquids.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] As can be seen in the chart, the liquids with the highest vapor pressures have the lowest normal boiling points.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] For example, at any given temperature, methyl chloride has the highest vapor pressure of any of the liquids in the chart.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] It also has the lowest normal boiling point (−24.2 °C), which is where the vapor pressure curve of methyl chloride (the blue line) intersects the horizontal pressure line of one atmosphere (atm) of absolute vapor pressure.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The critical point of a liquid is the highest temperature (and pressure) it will actually boil at.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The element with the lowest boiling point is helium.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Both the boiling points of rhenium and tungsten exceed 5000 K at standard pressure; because it is difficult to measure extreme temperatures precisely without bias, both have been cited in the literature as having the higher boiling point.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] As can be seen from the above plot of the logarithm of the vapor pressure vs. the temperature for any given pure chemical compound, its normal boiling point can serve as an indication of that compound's overall volatility.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] A given pure compound has only one normal boiling point, if any, and a compound's normal boiling point and melting point can serve as characteristic physical properties for that compound, listed in reference books.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The higher a compound's normal boiling point, the less volatile that compound is overall, and conversely, the lower a compound's normal boiling point, the more volatile that compound is overall.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Some compounds decompose at higher temperatures before reaching their normal boiling point, or sometimes even their melting point.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] For a stable compound, the boiling point ranges from its triple point to its critical point, depending on the external pressure.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Beyond its triple point, a compound's normal boiling point, if any, is higher than its melting point.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Beyond the critical point, a compound's liquid and vapor phases merge into one phase, which may be called a superheated gas.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] At any given temperature, if a compound's normal boiling point is lower, then that compound will generally exist as a gas at atmospheric external pressure.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] If the compound's normal boiling point is higher, then that compound can exist as a liquid or solid at that given temperature at atmospheric external pressure, and will so exist in equilibrium with its vapor (if volatile) if its vapors are contained.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] If a compound's vapors are not contained, then some volatile compounds can eventually evaporate away in spite of their higher boiling points.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] In general, compounds with ionic bonds have high normal boiling points, if they do not decompose before reaching such high temperatures.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Many metals have high boiling points, but not all.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Very generally—with other factors being equal—in compounds with covalently bonded molecules, as the size of the molecule (or molecular mass) increases, the normal boiling point increases.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] When the molecular size becomes that of a macromolecule, polymer, or otherwise very large, the compound often decomposes at high temperature before the boiling point is reached.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Another factor that affects the normal boiling point of a compound is the polarity of its molecules.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] As the polarity of a compound's molecules increases, its normal boiling point increases, other factors being equal.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Closely related is the ability of a molecule to form hydrogen bonds (in the liquid state), which makes it harder for molecules to leave the liquid state and thus increases the normal boiling point of the compound.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Simple carboxylic acids dimerize by forming hydrogen bonds between molecules.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] A minor factor affecting boiling points is the shape of a molecule.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Making the shape of a molecule more compact tends to lower the normal boiling point slightly compared to an equivalent molecule with more surface area.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Most volatile compounds (anywhere near ambient temperatures) go through an intermediate liquid phase while warming up from a solid phase to eventually transform to a vapor phase.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] By comparison to boiling, a sublimation is a physical transformation in which a solid turns directly into vapor, which happens in a few select cases such as with carbon dioxide at atmospheric pressure.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] For such compounds, a sublimation point is a temperature at which a solid turning directly into vapor has a vapor pressure equal to the external pressure.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] In the preceding section, boiling points of pure compounds were covered.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Vapor pressures and boiling points of substances can be affected by the presence of dissolved impurities (solutes) or other miscible compounds, the degree of effect depending on the concentration of the impurities or other compounds.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The presence of non-volatile impurities such as salts or compounds of a volatility far lower than the main component compound decreases its mole fraction and the solution's volatility, and thus raises the normal boiling point in proportion to the concentration of the solutes.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] This effect is called **boiling point elevation**.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] As a common example, salt water boils at a higher temperature than pure water.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] In other mixtures of miscible compounds (components), there may be two or more components of varying volatility, each having its own pure component boiling point at any given pressure.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The presence of other volatile components in a mixture affects the vapor pressures and thus boiling points and dew points of all the components in the mixture.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The dew point is a temperature at which a vapor condenses into a liquid.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Furthermore, at any given temperature, the composition of the vapor is different from the composition of the liquid in most such cases.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] In order to illustrate these effects between the volatile components in a mixture, a **boiling point diagram** is commonly used.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Distillation is a process of boiling and [usually] condensation which takes advantage of these differences in composition between liquid and vapor phases.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] This registry includes all substances described since 1957, plus some substances from as far back as the early 1800s.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] It is a chemical database that includes organic and inorganic compounds, minerals, isotopes, alloys, mixtures, and nonstructurable materials (UVCBs - substances of **u**nknown or **v**ariable composition, **c**omplex reaction products, or **b**iological origin).
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] CAS RNs are generally serial numbers (with a check digit), so they do not contain any information about the structures themselves the way SMILES and InChI strings do.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The CAS Registry is an authoritative collection of disclosed chemical substance information.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] It identifies more than 204 million unique organic and inorganic substances and 69 million protein and DNA sequences, plus additional information about each substance.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] It is updated with around 15,000 additional new substances daily.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The full registry is available on a paid subscription basis.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] A collection of almost 500 thousand CAS registry numbers is made available under a CC BY-NC license at ACS Commons Chemistry.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] Historically, chemicals have been identified by a wide variety of synonyms and properties.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] One of the biggest challenges in the early development of substance indexing, a task undertaken by the Chemical Abstracts Service, was in identifying if a substance in literature was new or if it had been previously discovered.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] Well-known chemicals may be known via multiple generic, historical, commercial, and/or (black)-market names, and even systematic nomenclature based on structure alone was not universally useful.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] An algorithm was developed to translate the structural formula of a chemical into a computer-searchable table, which provided a basis for the service that listed each chemical with its CAS Registry Number, the CAS Chemical Registry System, which became operational in 1965.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] CAS Registry Numbers (CAS RN) are simple and regular, convenient for database searches.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] They offer a reliable, common and international link to every specific substance across the various nomenclatures and disciplines used by branches of science, industry, and regulatory bodies.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] Almost all molecule databases today allow searching by CAS Registry Number, and it is used as a global standard.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] A CAS Registry Number has no inherent meaning, but is assigned in sequential, increasing order when the substance is identified by CAS scientists for inclusion in the CAS Registry database.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] A CAS RN is separated by hyphens into three parts, the first consisting from two up to seven digits, the second consisting of two digits, and the third consisting of a single digit serving as a check digit.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] This format gives CAS a maximum capacity of 1,000,000,000 unique numbers.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The check digit is found by taking the last digit times 1, the preceding digit times 2, the preceding digit times 3 etc., adding all these up and computing the sum modulo 10.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The CAS Registry accepts entries that are (1) descriptive of matter consisting of chemical elements, (2) distinct from existing ones, and (3) present in scientific literature.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The definition of "distinct" excludes different phases of the same substance (e.g. water and ice), but includes narrowing of existing concepts (e.g. carbon vs. graphite and diamond; isotope-labelled forms of an existing compound).
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The Chemical Abstracts Service subscription includes an official search service.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The Service ("CAS Data") provides information on the chemical itself, its mentions in published scholarly works and patents, curated biological and chemical reaction data, as well as listings of commercial sources and details on using a substance in a formulation.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] A subset of the registry can be accessed through the free-of-charge CAS Common Chemistry, which provides identifying information for the chemical in question.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] The name ***Cellosolve*** was registered in 1924 as a United States trademark by Carbide & Carbon Chemicals Corporation (a division of Union Carbide Corporation) for "Solvents for Gums, Resins, Cellulose Esters, and the Like".
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] *Ethyl Cellosolve*, or simply *Cellosolve*, consists mainly of ethylene glycol monoethyl ether and was introduced as a lower-cost solvent alternative to ethyl lactate.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] *Butyl Cellosolve* (ethylene glycol monobutyl ether) was introduced in 1928, and *Methyl Cellosolve* (ethylene glycol monomethyl ether) in 1929.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] Glycol ethers are designated *E-series* or *P-series* for those made from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide, respectively.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] Typically, E-series glycol ethers are found in pharmaceuticals, sunscreens, cosmetics, inks, dyes and water-based paints, while P-series glycol ethers are used in degreasers, cleaners, aerosol paints and adhesives.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] Both E- and P-series glycol ethers can be used as intermediates that undergo further chemical reactions, producing glycol diethers and glycol ether acetates.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] P-series glycol ethers are marketed as having lower toxicity than the E-series.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] Most glycol ethers are water-soluble, biodegradable and only a few are considered toxic.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] One study suggests that occupational exposure to glycol ethers is related to lowering the motility of the sperm and sperm count, a finding disputed by the chemical industry.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chebi] ChEBI uses nomenclature, symbolism and terminology endorsed by the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) and nomenclature committee of the International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology (NC-IUBMB).
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chebi] All data in the database is non-proprietary or is derived from a non-proprietary source.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chebi] It is thus freely accessible and available to anyone.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chebi] In addition, each data item is fully traceable and explicitly referenced to the original source.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chebi] It is related in scope to other databases such as ChEMBL, ChemSpider, DrugBank, MetaboLights and PubChem.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chebi] ChEBI data is available through a public web application, web services, SPARQL endpoint and downloads.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] The database, originally known as StARlite, was developed by a biotechnology company called Inpharmatica Ltd. later acquired by Galapagos NV.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] The data was acquired for EMBL in 2008 with an award from The Wellcome Trust, resulting in the creation of the ChEMBL chemogenomics group at EMBL-EBI, led by John Overington.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] The ChEMBL database contains compound bioactivity data against drug targets.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] Bioactivity is reported in Ki, Kd, IC50, and EC50.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] Data can be filtered and analyzed to develop compound screening libraries for lead identification during drug discovery.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] ChEMBL version 2 (ChEMBL_02) was launched in January 2010, including 2.4 million bioassay measurements covering 622,824 compounds, including 24,000 natural products.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] This was obtained from curating over 34,000 publications across twelve medicinal chemistry journals.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] ChEMBL's coverage of available bioactivity data has grown to become "the most comprehensive ever seen in a public database.".
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] In October 2010 ChEMBL version 8 (ChEMBL_08) was launched, with over 2.97 million bioassay measurements covering 636,269 compounds.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] ChEMBL_10 saw the addition of the PubChem confirmatory assays, in order to integrate data that is comparable to the type and class of data contained within ChEMBL.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] ChEMBLdb can be accessed via a web interface or downloaded by File Transfer Protocol.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] It is formatted in a manner amenable to computerized data mining, and attempts to standardize activities between different publications, to enable comparative analysis.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] ChEMBL is also integrated into other large-scale chemistry resources, including PubChem and the ChemSpider system of the Royal Society of Chemistry.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] In addition to the database, the ChEMBL group have developed tools and resources for data mining.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] These include Kinase SARfari, an integrated chemogenomics workbench focussed on kinases.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] The system incorporates and links sequence, structure, compounds and screening data.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] GPCR SARfari is a similar workbench focused on GPCRs, and ChEMBL-Neglected Tropical Diseases (ChEMBL-NTD) is a repository for Open Access primary screening and medicinal chemistry data directed at endemic tropical diseases of the developing regions of the Africa, Asia, and the Americas.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] The primary purpose of ChEMBL-NTD is to provide a freely accessible and permanent archive and distribution centre for deposited data.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] July 2012 saw the release of a new malaria data service Archived 2016-07-30 at the Wayback Machine, sponsored by the Medicines for Malaria Venture (MMV), aimed at researchers around the globe.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] The data in this service includes compounds from the Malaria Box screening set, as well as the other donated malaria data found in ChEMBL-NTD.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] myChEMBL, the ChEMBL virtual machine, was released in October 2013 to allow users to access a complete and free, easy-to-install cheminformatics infrastructure.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] In December 2013, the operations of the SureChem patent informatics database were transferred to EMBL-EBI.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] In a portmanteau, SureChem was renamed SureChEMBL.
[src:2-2-ethoxyethoxy-ethanol/chembl] 2014 saw the introduction of the new resource ADME SARfari - a tool for predicting and comparing cross-species ADME targets.
